Linear Regression

  • Better understand the relationship between two variables
    • A dependent variable y and an independent variable x
  • What is the association between these two variables?
    • What is the trend (positive, neutral, negative)?
    • What is the strength of the relationship? (How correlated are the variables)

Estimation

  • Before running linear regression, always good to look at the scatterplot to see if there is a linear relationship between y and x

Ordinary Least Squares

  • We use ordinary least squares to estimate slope and intercept of the best fit line.
  • Best fit line minimizes the sum of the residuals for all the observed data points.

Residuals

lm()

You can use lm() to run a linear regression in R.

Formula only needs to include the response (variable on the y axis) and predictors (variable on the x-axis)

Output

mod_e <- wages %>% lm(log(income)~ education, data=.)

Output

  • Slope determines the direction and strength of the relationship between the two variables.
    • It is the change in the number of units of the dependent variable associated with an increase of 1 unit of the independent variable.
    • Slope = 0 \(\rightarrow\) no association
    • Slope > 0 \(\rightarrow\) y increases with increases in x
    • Slope < 0 \(\rightarrow\) y decreases with increases in x

Model diagnostics

  • After fitting a model, its necessary to check the model to see if it fits the data well.
  • You can use the functions in the broom package to assess your model.

  • Standard error determines how uncertain the estimates are.
    • Larger standard error \(\rightarrow\) more uncertainty
    • Standard errors characterize how well the best-fitting line models the data.
    • The closer the points are to the line, the lower the standard error will be.

p-value

  • The p-value is a single number that takes into account both the estimate and the uncertainty in that estimate.
  • “the probability of getting the observed results (or results more extreme) by chance alone.”
  • The lower the p-value, the more significant the association is between two variables.
  • Does not tell you as much information as reporting the estimates and standard errors directly.
  • If you report a p-value, its best to also include the estimate (and standard error)

When carrying out inferential data analysis, you will always want to report an estimate and a measure of uncertainty. For linear regression, this will be the slope estimate and the corresponding standard error.

broom package functions

tidy() returns model coefficients standard errors and the p-values for each parameter. It tells you what uncertainty is associated with each parameter in the model (intercept and slope)?

library(broom)
mod_e %>% tidy()
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)    8.56    0.0733      117.  0        
## 2 education      0.142   0.00530      26.7 8.41e-148

glance()

glance() returns model diagnostics. It tells you whether linear model is good for describing the relationship between the two variables.

Correlation is not causation

  • The regression only gives the association between the variables.
  • Always keep this in mind that never draw causal claims when all you have are associations.

Multivariate Regression

The multivariate regression is similar to linear regression, except that it accommodates for multiple independent variables. It finds the relationship between the dependent variable and each independent variable, while controlling for all other variables.

mod_eh <- wages %>% 
  lm(log(income) ~ education + height, data = .)
mod_eh %>% tidy()

The coefficient is the change in the number of units of the dependent variable associated with an increase of 1 unit of the independent variable, controlling for the other independent variables.

wages %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = height, y = log(income))) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1) +
    geom_smooth(method = loess)
